It can be noted that the presence of carbon peak for different input voltages with the binding energy of 284.93 eV in photoelectron spectra could be attributed to graphitic and diamond phases composed of hybridizations of sp2 and sp3 (Fig. 4
                        ) [36]. The intensity of the binding energy is linearly proportional to the fraction of sp3 and sp2 bonds and the ionization cross sections are independent of the chemical state of the atoms for X-ray photons having energy well above the ionization threshold. The deconvolution of the obtained spectra through Gaussian fitting exhibits the presence of sp3 and sp2 hybridizations [4,37]. For the sample processed at 700 V, the carbon peak was found to be at 286.62 eV which is 2.47 eV higher than the graphite (284.15 eV) this could be attributed to the high energy plasmatic effect occurring due to the higher plasma process voltage. Main peak, is observed at 285.0 eV, 285.32 eV and 285.36 eV (Fig. 5
                        ) for different plasma voltages of 700 V, 800 V and 900 V respectively for the CC stretching [38]. In the spectra sp3 which exhibits the lower and higher hybridized peaks at 285.36 eV and 533.71 eV which may be due to the existence of CC and CO-H bonding. Fig. 4 shows the corresponding peaks shifting with OC-O groups. The corresponding values are given in the Table 2
                        .
